Citations
Date:  0/0/1904
Source:  Maori Race, The
Author:  TREGEAR
Vol / Page:  204
Edition:
Quote:  The third curse (<i>tapatapa</i>) was to call anything by a person's name ... For instance, if a chief <i>taptapa'</i>d a spear by saying that it was one of his legs, it became his property ...
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1855
Source:  Te Ika a Maui
Author:  Taylor
Vol / Page:  94
Edition:
Quote:  Another way of obtaining revenge was by cursing. To call any object by the name of a chief, and then strike or insult it, was regarded as a curse; this was tapatapa or tukutuku.
Notes:

Date:  31/3/1852
Source:  New Zealander, The
Author:
Vol / Page:  2
Edition:
Quote:  .. and it is not uncommon to hear a chief complain that he has been shot at, when on explanation it appears that he has only been shot in effigy. This form of insult is called a "tapatapa" or "tukutuku".
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1907
Source:  Proceedings RSNZ
Author:
Vol / Page:  40/198
Edition:
Quote:  .. were a chief to become aware that a chief of a neighbouring district had used some insulting expression towards him, he might tapu the track leading to that district, which would cause much inconvenience until it was reopened. That particular kind of insult known as a tapatapa might cause such an action.
